 -- tThe Earliest Evidence of an Emerging Christian Material and Visual Culture: The Codex, The Nomina Sacra and the Staurogram -- tThe Aesthetic Origins of Early Christian Architecture -- t"Ascent and Descent" in the Constantinian Church of the Nativity in Bethlehem -- tText and Artifact in the World of Late-Antique Judaism -- tBetter Homes and Gardens: Women and Domestic Space in the Books of Judith and Susanna -- tTyros, The "Floating Palace" -- tOI IIOTE IOΥΔAIOI: Epigraphic Evidence for Jewish Defectors -- tJerusalem Ossuary Inscriptions and the Status of Jewish Proselytes -- tBehind the Names: Samaritans, Ioudaioi, Galileans -- tFriendship and Second Temple Jewish Sectarianism -- tWhat Josephus Says about the Essenes in his Judean War -- tThe Archaeological Artifacts of Masada and the Credibility of Josephus -- tMishnah's Rhetoric, Other Material Artifacts of Late-Roman Galilee and the Social Formation of the Early Rabbinic Guild -- tText and Artifact in the Grecoroman World -- tSome Thoughts on Theurgy -- tApuleius to Symmachus (and Stops in Between): Pietas, Real1a and the Empire -- tApuleius the Novelist, Apuleius the Ostian Householder and the Mithraeum of the Seven Spheres: Further Explorations of an Hypothesis of Filippo Coarelli -- tIndices -- tModern Authors Index -- tAncient Sources Index -- tSubject Index -- tSeries Published by Wilfrid Laurier University Press for the Canadian Corporation for Studies in Religion/ Corporation Canadienne des Sciences Religieuses0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCan archaeological remains be made to “speak” when brought into conjunction with texts? Can written remains, on stone or papyrus, shed light on the parables of Jesus, or on the Jewish view of afterlife? What are the limits to the use of artifactual data, and when is the value overstated? Text and Artifact addresses the complex and intriguing issue of how primary religious texts from the ancient Mediterranean world are illuminated by, and in turn illuminate, the ever-increasing amount of artifactual evidence available from the surrounding world. The book honours Peter Richardson, and the first two chapters offer appreciations of this scholarship and teaching. The remaining chapters focus on early Christianity, late-antique Judaism and topics germane to the Roman world at large. Many of the essays relate to features of Jewish life — the epigraphic evidence for gentile converts to Judaism or for Jewish defectors, ancient accounts of the Essenes or of the siege of Masada, and the material context of the first great rabbinic work, the Mishnah. Other essays connect early Christian texts with the social and cultural realia of their day — modes of travel, notions of gender, patronage and benefaction, the relation of tenants and owners — or reflect on the aesthetics of Christian architecture and the relation between building and ritual in Constantinian churches. One study relates the writing of the famous novelist Apuleius to a household mithraeum in Ostia, while another explores the changing appropriation of religious realia as the Roman world became Christian. These wide-ranging and original studies demonstrate clearly that texts and artifacts can be mutually supportive. Equally, they point to ways in which artifacts, no less than texts, are inherently ambiguous and teach us to be cautious in our conclusions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChurch historyxPrimitive and early church, ca. 30-600. 0aChurch historyyPrimitive and early church, ca. 30-600. 0aJews in the New Testament. 0aJudaismxHistoryxPost-exilic period, 586 B.C.-210 A.D. 0aJudaismxHistoryyPost-exilic period, 586 B.C.-210 A.D. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh1 aAnn Jervis, L., econt